T1  - Induced work participation and the returns to experience for welfare women: Evidence from a social experiment
AU  - Steinberg, Dan
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 41
IS  - 3
SP  - 321
EP  - 340
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/07/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(89)90065-1
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407689900651
AB  - In the late 1970's, a welfare reform experiment with 'workfare'-like provisions was conducted in Minnesota. The experiment provided education and training to AFDC recipients in an attempt to improve client long-term labor-market outcomes. An evaluation of the experiment applying simultaneous-equations modeling of outcomes, attrition, and endogenously missing data is presented. We find imprecise evidence that the program increased the probability of post-program work participation, and we measure a high rate of return in wages to work experience. Although we find no evidence of attrition bias, there is considerable influence of selectivity in the wage equations.
